    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "The following piece of code ends up accessing the `cython_runtime` module when its reference count is 0 and its destructor has already been called. This is undefined behaviour and can cause the interpreter to crash.\r\n\r\n```python\r\nimport sys\r\n\r\ndef generator():\r\n    yield\r\n    yield\r\n\r\ng = generator()\r\nnext(g)\r\n\r\ndel sys.modules[\"cython_runtime\"]\r\ndel g\r\n```\r\n\r\nEven if `sys.modules[\"cython_runtime\"]` is not deleted explicitly, the bug can still occur during shutdown depending on whether the reference count for `g` or `cython_runtime` goes down to 0 first.\r\n\r\nThe problem is caused by `__Pyx_CLineForTraceback` being called when stopping a started generator and trying to look up the `cython_runtime.cline_in_traceback` variable introduced in 0.26. See [Exceptions.c#L665](https://github.com/cython/cython/blob/0.29.6/Cython/Utility/Exceptions.c#L665) and [Exceptions.c#L673](https://github.com/cython/cython/blob/0.29.6/Cython/Utility/Exceptions.c#L673).\r\n\r\nIt only has a borrowed reference to `cython_runtime` from [ModuleNode.py#L2839](https://github.com/cython/cython/blob/master/Cython/Compiler/ModuleNode.py#L2839) obtained during initialisation which is not reference counted and thus there is no guarantee that the object has not already been destroyed.\r\n\r\nI believe adding a call to `code.put_incref()` after obtaining the reference would be sufficient to resolve the issue, but there may be better ways of going about this.\r\n\r\nNote that this particular example is not guaranteed to crash. However I confirmed the illegal access by\r\nbreaking at the lines mentioned above in a debugger, and seeing that `__pyx_cython_runtime->ob_refcnt` is 0 at the point of access.",
    "closed_at": "2019-03-04T14:56:56Z",
